WEBVTT

1
00:00:13.527 --> 00:00:16.416
People back home call me a heckler,
家乡的人们称为我诘问者，

2
00:00:16.416 --> 00:00:19.133
a troublemaker, an irritant,
麻烦制造者，激进者，

3
00:00:19.133 --> 00:00:21.803
a rebel, an activist,
反抗者，行动主义者，

4
00:00:21.803 --> 00:00:23.660
the voice of the people.
人民的声音。

5
00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:25.830
But that wasn't always me.
但我并不是从小就这样。

6
00:00:26.470 --> 00:00:28.002
Growing up, I had a nickname.
小的时候我有一个绰号，

7
00:00:28.002 --> 00:00:30.322
They used to call me Softy,
他们叫我「软蛋」，

8
00:00:30.322 --> 00:00:33.575
meaning the soft, harmless boy.
这个词意味着软弱，不惹麻烦，

9
00:00:33.575 --> 00:00:36.315
Like every other human being, I avoided trouble.
像其他人一样，避免麻烦。

10
00:00:36.315 --> 00:00:38.358
In my childhood, they taught me silence.
小的时候，他们教我要保持安静。

11
00:00:38.358 --> 00:00:40.160
Don't argue, do as you're told.
不去争辩，让你做什么你就听话。

12
00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:44.092
In Sunday school, they taught me don't confront, don't argue,
在主日学校，他们教我不要反对，不要争辩，

13
00:00:44.092 --> 00:00:47.405
even if you're right, turn the other cheek.
即便你有理，也要容忍。

14
00:00:47.405 --> 00:00:52.002
This was reinforced by the political climate of the time.
当时的政治风气加重了「软蛋」之风。

15
00:00:52.002 --> 00:00:55.603
(Laughter)
（笑声）

16
00:00:55.603 --> 00:01:00.059
Kenya is a country where you are guilty until proven rich.
在肯尼亚，唯有腰包鼓才可以是良民。

17
00:01:00.059 --> 00:01:02.804
(Laughter)
（笑声）

18
00:01:02.804 --> 00:01:05.546
Kenya's poor are five times more likely
相比于被罪犯杀害，

19
00:01:05.546 --> 00:01:10.118
to be shot dead by the police who are meant to protect them than by criminals.
肯尼亚的穷人有六倍高的可能性被那些应该保护他们的警察射杀。

20
00:01:10.118 --> 00:01:12.765
This was reinforced by the political climate of the day.
当时的政治环境恶化了这种气焰。

21
00:01:12.765 --> 00:01:15.714
We had a president, Moi, who was a dictator.
我的总统Moi是一个独裁者。

22
00:01:15.714 --> 00:01:17.920
He ruled the country with an iron fist,
他用铁拳统治着国家，

23
00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:20.358
and anyone who dared question his authority
任何人若敢质疑他的权威，

24
00:01:20.358 --> 00:01:25.327
was arrested, tortured, jailed or even killed.
会被逮捕，施加酷刑，锒铛入狱，甚至会被杀害。

25
00:01:25.327 --> 00:01:29.251
That meant that people were taught to be smart cowards, stay out of trouble.
这意味着人民要学聪明，而不是惹麻烦。

26
00:01:29.251 --> 00:01:31.294
Being a coward was not an insult.
变成「软蛋」不再是一种耻辱，

27
00:01:31.294 --> 00:01:33.221
Being a coward was a compliment.
而是一种荣耀。

28
00:01:33.221 --> 00:01:36.379
We used to be told that a coward goes home to his mother.
俗话说「懦夫才能找到回家的路。」

29
00:01:36.379 --> 00:01:40.140
What that meant: that if you stayed out of trouble you're going to stay alive.
其含义是：不惹麻烦，才能活着回家。

30
00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:42.080
I used to question this advice,
我质疑过这种说法，

31
00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.902
and eight years ago we had an election in Kenya,
8年前，肯尼亚的选举过后，

32
00:01:44.902 --> 00:01:47.385
and the results were violently disputed.
爆发了激烈的政治斗争。

33
00:01:47.385 --> 00:01:52.122
What followed that election was terrible violence, rape,
随之而来的是恐怖的暴力和强奸事件，

34
00:01:52.122 --> 00:01:56.059
and the killing of over 1,000 people.
超过一千人丧失了性命。

35
00:01:56.059 --> 00:01:59.180
My work was to document the violence.
我的工作是记录这场动乱。

36
00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:02.036
As a photographer, I took thousands of images,
作为一个摄影师，我拍了上千幅照片。

37
00:02:02.036 --> 00:02:04.103
and after two months,
两个月之后，

38
00:02:04.103 --> 00:02:08.978
the two politicians came together, had a cup of tea,
双方坐在谈判桌前，泡上一杯茶，

39
00:02:08.978 --> 00:02:12.415
signed a peace agreement, and the country moved on.
签订了和平协议，这事就这么过去了。

40
00:02:12.415 --> 00:02:15.944
I was a very disturbed man because I saw the violence firsthand.
我内心十分不安，因为我目睹了暴力事件。

41
00:02:15.944 --> 00:02:19.550
I saw the killings. I saw the displacement.
我目睹了残杀。我目睹了政权更迭。

42
00:02:19.550 --> 00:02:22.631
I met women who had been raped, and it disturbed me,
我目睹了强奸惨案。这让我很不安，

43
00:02:22.631 --> 00:02:24.675
but the country never spoke about it.
但国家却保持缄默，

44
00:02:24.675 --> 00:02:27.159
We pretended. We all became smart cowards.
我们假装，我们聪明地畏缩起来。

45
00:02:27.159 --> 00:02:30.758
We decided to stay out of trouble and not talk about it.
我们不想惹麻烦，不去谈论这一切。

46
00:02:30.758 --> 00:02:34.055
Ten months later, I quit my job. I said I could not stand it anymore.
十个月之后，我辞去了工作。我再也不能忍气吞声。

47
00:02:34.055 --> 00:02:38.670
After quitting my job, I decided to organize my friends to speak about the violence in the country,
辞去工作以后，我决定召集朋友们一起发出一些声音，

48
00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:40.534
to speak about the state of the nation,
不让那场惨案和整个国家沉寂于无形。

49
00:02:40.534 --> 00:02:44.650
and June 1, 2009 was the day that we were meant to go to the stadium
我们打算在2009年6月1日那一天去会堂做些什么，

50
00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:46.709
and try and get the president's attention.
引起总统的注意。

51
00:02:46.709 --> 00:02:48.149
It's a national holiday,
那一天是国定假日，

52
00:02:47.909 --> 00:02:49.798
it's broadcast across the country,
全国直播，

53
00:02:49.798 --> 00:02:53.206
and I showed up at the stadium.
我到了会堂，

54
00:02:53.206 --> 00:02:56.200
My friends did not show up.
我的朋友们却没有来。

55
00:02:56.200 --> 00:02:59.573
I found myself alone,
孤立无援的我

56
00:03:00.033 --> 00:03:02.100
and I didn't know what to do.
不知所措，

57
00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:03.515
I was scared,
虽然惊慌，

58
00:03:03.515 --> 00:03:05.685
but I knew very well that that particular day,
但我内心很明确，在这特殊的一天，

59
00:03:05.685 --> 00:03:06.906
I had to make a decision.
我必须做出决定。

60
00:03:06.906 --> 00:03:09.329
Was I able to live as a coward, like everyone else,
我是继续像所有人一样做一个懦夫，

61
00:03:09.329 --> 00:03:10.927
or was I going to make a stand?
还是挺身而出？

62
00:03:10.927 --> 00:03:13.133
And when the president stood up to speak,
当总统起身演讲时，

63
00:03:13.133 --> 00:03:17.740
I found myself on my feet shouting at the president,
我站了起来，对总统呐喊，

64
00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:20.934
telling him to remember the post-election violence victims,
告诉他要记住选举后的动乱受害者，

65
00:03:20.934 --> 00:03:23.210
to stop the corruption.
要遏制腐败。

66
00:03:23.210 --> 00:03:25.415
And suddenly, out of nowhere,
突然，不知从哪窜出来的警察

67
00:03:25.415 --> 00:03:28.527
the police pounced on me like hungry lions.
像饿虎扑食一样想我扑来。

68
00:03:28.527 --> 00:03:30.384
They held my mouth
他们钳住了我的嘴，

69
00:03:30.384 --> 00:03:32.311
and dragged me out of the stadium,
把我拖出了会场，

70
00:03:32.311 --> 00:03:35.282
where they thoroughly beat me up and locked me up in jail.
随后痛打一番，铐起来关到监狱里。

71
00:03:36.932 --> 00:03:43.690
I spent that night in a cold cement floor in the jail,
那一晚我在监狱冰冷的水泥地上度过，

72
00:03:43.690 --> 00:03:46.338
and that got me thinking.
这不禁让我思考。

73
00:03:46.338 --> 00:03:48.209
What was making me feel this way?
是什么让我从懦夫变成勇夫的？

74
00:03:48.209 --> 00:03:51.374
My friends and family thought I was crazy because of what I did,
我的朋友们和家人看到我的所作所为都觉得我疯了，

75
00:03:51.374 --> 00:03:56.388
and the images that I took were disturbing my life.
还拍了那么多照片。

76
00:03:56.388 --> 00:03:59.338
The images that I took were just a number to many Kenyans.
这些令我不安的照片对很多肯尼亚人而言只是一个数字。

77
00:03:59.338 --> 00:04:01.285
Most Kenyans did not see the violence.
大多肯尼亚人没有目睹那场暴力，

78
00:04:01.285 --> 00:04:02.980
It was a story to them.
对于他们而言不过是个故事。

79
00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.767
And so I decided to actually start a street exhibition
因此我决定举办一场展览，

80
00:04:05.767 --> 00:04:08.553
to show the images of the violence across the country
在全国各地的街道上展出暴力事件的照片，

81
00:04:08.553 --> 00:04:10.527
and get people talking about it.
让民众谈论它们。

82
00:04:10.527 --> 00:04:13.336
We traveled the country and showed the images,
我们的足迹遍布全国，展示照片，

83
00:04:13.336 --> 00:04:16.819
and this was a journey that has started me to the activist path,
由此我踏上了行动主义者之路。

84
00:04:16.819 --> 00:04:19.536
where I decided to become silent no more,
我下定决心，不再保持沉默，

85
00:04:19.536 --> 00:04:21.734
to talk about those things.
要高声谈论那些事情。

86
00:04:21.734 --> 00:04:25.384
We traveled, and our general site from our street exhibit
随着我们的脚步，我们从展出照片

87
00:04:25.384 --> 00:04:30.182
became for political graffiti about the situation in the country,
转变为反映现实的政治涂鸦，

88
00:04:30.182 --> 00:04:32.940
talking about corruption, bad leadership.
披露腐败作风和领导者的失职。

89
00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:36.720
We have even done symbolic burials.
我们甚至还办了象征性葬礼。

90
00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:40.702
We have delivered live pigs to Kenya's parliament
我们把一头活猪送到了肯尼亚议会，

91
00:04:40.702 --> 00:04:42.630
as a symbol of our politicians' greed.
用以讽刺政客的贪婪。

92
00:04:42.630 --> 00:04:44.861
It has been done in Uganda and other countries,
在乌干达和其他国家也有人做这样的事，

93
00:04:44.861 --> 00:04:48.370
and what is most powerful is that the images have been picked by the media
最激动人心的是媒体捕捉到了这些画面，

94
00:04:48.370 --> 00:04:51.406
and amplified across the country, across the continent.
并大肆宣传，传遍祖国大地，横越整个大陆。

95
00:04:51.406 --> 00:04:54.053
Where I used to stand up alone seven years ago,
七年前独自挺身而出的我，

96
00:04:54.053 --> 00:04:57.079
now I belong to a community of many people who stand up with me.
如今找到了组织，很多人会跟我一起挺身而出。

97
00:04:57.079 --> 00:05:01.407
I am no longer alone when I stand up to speak about these things.
我为这些事情呐喊时不再是孤身一人。

98
00:05:01.997 --> 00:05:06.170
I belong to a group of young people who are passionate about the country,
我们这个年轻人团体对祖国充满了热爱，

99
00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:08.020
who want to bring about change,
力图革新，

100
00:05:08.020 --> 00:05:12.434
and they're no longer afraid, and they're no longer smart cowards.
不再畏惧，摒弃了懦夫形象。

101
00:05:13.564 --> 00:05:16.292
So that was my story.
这就是我的故事，

102
00:05:18.062 --> 00:05:20.660
That day in the stadium,
那天在会场里，

103
00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:23.147
I stood up as a smart coward.
站起来之前我还是一个懦夫，

104
00:05:23.147 --> 00:05:28.394
By that one action, I said goodbye to the 24 years living as a coward.
但那一站，让我告别了24年懦弱的生命。

105
00:05:28.394 --> 00:05:31.436
There are two most powerful days in your life:
人的生命中有两天是尤为可贵的：

106
00:05:31.436 --> 00:05:35.982
the day you're born, and the day you discover why.
你出生的那一天，你想明白的那一天。

107
00:05:36.591 --> 00:05:39.835
That day standing up in that stadium shouting at the President,
在会场里站起来对总统呐喊的那一天，

108
00:05:39.835 --> 00:05:43.115
I discovered why I was truly born,
我明白了我为什么要存活在这个世界上：

109
00:05:43.115 --> 00:05:46.366
that I would no longer be silent in the face of injustice.
不公正面前不再沉默。

110
00:05:47.596 --> 00:05:50.400
Do you know why you were born?
你发现你活着的意义了吗？

111
00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:53.355
Thank you.
谢谢。

112
00:05:52.175 --> 00:05:58.274
(Applause)
（掌声）

113
00:06:00.344 --> 00:06:02.851
Tom Rielly: It's an amazing story.
Tom Rielly: 这个故事太不可思议了。

114
00:06:02.851 --> 00:06:05.407
I just want to ask you a couple quick questions.
有些问题我非常想问你。

115
00:06:05.407 --> 00:06:07.727
So PAWA254:
那么 PAWA254：

116
00:06:07.727 --> 00:06:12.040
you've created a studio, a place where young people can go
你创立过一个录音室，年轻人可以到你那，

117
00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:16.507
and harness the power of digital media to do some of this action.
利用强大的数字媒体去做一些事。

118
00:06:16.507 --> 00:06:18.384
What's happening now with PAWA?
PAWA现在怎么样了？

119
00:06:18.384 --> 00:06:21.167
Boniface Mwangi: So we have  this community of filmmakers,
Boniface Mwangi: 我们这个团体里有制片人，

120
00:06:21.167 --> 00:06:24.530
graffiti artists, musicians, and when there's an issue in the country,
涂鸦艺术家，音乐家，当我们国家发生了些什么，

121
00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:27.331
we come together, we brainstorm, and take up on that issue.
我们会聚在一起，头脑风暴，解决这些事。

122
00:06:27.331 --> 00:06:29.387
So our most powerful tool is art,
我们最强大的工具是艺术，

123
00:06:29.387 --> 00:06:33.218
because we live in a very busy world where people are so busy in their life,
因为在今天这个繁忙的世界里，人们都忙着自己的事情，

124
00:06:33.218 --> 00:06:35.285
and they don't have time to read.
没有时间阅读。

125
00:06:35.285 --> 00:06:39.418
So we package our activism and we package our message in art.
因此我们提炼出精华，以艺术的形式展现出来，

126
00:06:39.418 --> 00:06:44.397
So from the music, the graffiti,  the art, that's what we do.
如音乐、涂鸦，艺术，这就是我们所做的。

127
00:06:45.377 --> 00:06:47.405
Can I say one more thing?
我还能补充一些吗？

128
00:06:46.725 --> 00:06:48.926
TR: Yeah, of course. (Applause)
TR: 当然 （掌声）

129
00:06:48.926 --> 00:06:51.921
BM: In spite of being arrested, beaten up, threatened,
BM: 尽管被逮捕，被殴打，被威胁，

130
00:06:51.921 --> 00:06:53.634
the moment I discovered my voice,
但当我听到自己的声音的时候，

131
00:06:53.634 --> 00:06:56.530
that I could actually stand up for what I really believed in,
我可以为自己的信仰挺身而出，

132
00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:57.008
I'm no longer afraid.
我不再害怕。

133
00:06:57.568 --> 00:07:00.310
I used to be called softy, but I'm no longer softy,
我过去被人叫做「软蛋」，但我不再软弱，

134
00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:03.711
because I discovered who I really am, as in, that's what I want to do,
因为我真正地发现了自己是怎样的人，我真正地发现了我想做的事情，

135
00:07:03.711 --> 00:07:06.747
and there's such beauty in doing that.
行动的过程又如此美妙。

136
00:07:06.747 --> 00:07:10.136
There's nothing as powerful as that, knowing that I'm meant to do this,
生当如此，是再伟大的事情不过，

137
00:07:10.136 --> 00:07:13.283
because you don't get scared, you just continue living your life.
因为你会挺起胸膛生活，不再畏缩。

138
00:07:12.913 --> 00:07:13.689
Thank you.
谢谢。

139
00:07:13.689 --> 00:07:19.059
(Applause)
（掌声）